A.

There is a very remarkable characteristic of the style of these letters, not hitherto dwelt on‚* so far as I am aware-a very close parallelism between their diction and the diction of the comio drama.† It is, indeed, to be expected a priori that the language of familiar letter-writing would closely resemble the language of familiar dialogue. In both cases the language may be expected to ·be largely tinged with the idiom of the sermo vulyaris, or collo- quialiam.‡ Cicero, in an important passage,§ recognises the collo- quial character of his letters, referring, no doubt, especially to those which we have spoken of as his more private letters, namely, those

to Atticus, Trebatius, Caclius, and his brother Quintus. It would 118 impossible for me here to enter into an elaborate comparison

between the language of Cicero's letter and that of the comio stage.
